”’Ů@ee246bf6bd0319336eece2df8fc079da13b5e0dc77325eee96f72eca7ce5d56dŮÄTitle: title: Nushell Bashisms
Path: Bashisms
Content:




A frequently asked question is, "What bashims does Nushell support?". Frequently these questions revolve around bang bang functionality.
’Ů@5fa349523a25407033f1b8d8a6deaae39c3660b372e5b52538f67cc657d41173ŮžTitle: title: Nushell Bashisms
Path: What is a bashism
Content:
A bashism is a command, operator, or syntax in the repl that most people associate with bash.
’Ů@e4158a52ca3500725fe58ec2c5c7ef18489b13356071ba715222f87a876f0923ÚťTitle: title: Nushell Bashisms
Path: Bang Bang syntax
Content:
In reedline we support these bashisms.
``!!``
 - Repeat the last command.
``!n``
 - Repeat the nth command from your nushell history.
``!-n``
 - Repeat the nth command from your last history entry.
``!$``
 - Get the last spatially separated token from the last command in your history.
``!term``
 - Repeat the last command match a strings beginning.
’Ů@8bb7aaa8123d31b84db7563ab5af5058dafff10c32073bfe7218d53a2feec69fŮóTitle: title: Nushell Bashisms
Path: How to invoke bang bang syntax
Content:
In nushell when you type a bang command, it performs that functionality and places the result in the nushell command line buffer in the repl. It does not execute it.
